METHODOLOGY:
This bill extends eligibility for certain customer-generators used by political subdivisions to
receivecompensationunderthePublicUtilitiesCommission’salternativenet-meteringtariffsfor
aminimumtermandestablishesconditionsfortransitioningtofuturetariffs.
The Department of Energy states this bill will result in an increase in state expenditures
beginning in FY 2027. The bill is expected to increase the number of municipal group net-
metering and interconnection applications requiring review and processing, which the
Department indicates cannot be absorbed within existing staffing. The Department anticipates
the need for one full-time Business Specialist (SOC13-07) to support the additional workload.
Theestimatedcostforthispositionis$121,000inFY2027,$125,000inFY2028and$126,000in
FY 2029. These expenditures would be paid from the Renewable Energy Fund (REF). If these
positions are authorized, it is assumed the funding for these positions would be included in the
Department'sFY2028-FY2029budgetrequest.
The Public Utilities Commission states they could absorb the new requirements within this bill
intotheirexistingbudget.
